- **Apache Log4j Asynchronous Logging**:
  - Use `AsyncLogger` and `AsyncAppender`.
  - Example configuration in `log4j2.xml`:
    ```xml
    <Configuration status="WARN">
      <Appenders>
        <Console name="Console" target="SYSTEM_OUT">
          <PatternLayout pattern="%d{yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss} %-5p %c{1}:%L - %m%n"/>
        </Console>
        <Async name="Async">
          <AppenderRef ref="Console"/>
        </Async>
      </Appenders>
      <Loggers>
        <Root level="info">
          <AppenderRef ref="Async"/>
        </Root>
      </Loggers>
    </Configuration>
    ```

- **Java Asynchronous Logging**:
  - Use `java.util.concurrent.Executors` to create a thread pool.
  - Example:
    ```java
    import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;
    import java.util.concurrent.Executors;

    public class AsyncLoggingExample {
        private static final ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(10);

        public void log(String message) {
            executor.execute(() -> System.out.println("Log: " + message));
        }

        public static void main(String[] args) {
            AsyncLoggingExample example = new AsyncLoggingExample();
            for (int i = 0; i < 20; i++) {
                example.log("Message " + i);
            }
        }
    }
    ```

- **Spring Boot Asynchronous Logging**:
  - Enable asynchronous logging in `application.properties`:
    ```properties
    logging.level.root=INFO
    logging.pattern.console=%d{yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss} %-5p %c{1}:%L - %m%n
    ```
  - Use `@Async` annotation on methods to enable asynchronous execution.

- **spdlog Asynchronous Logging**:
  - Include spdlog in your project.
  - Example usage:
    ```cpp
    #include "spdlog/spdlog.h"
    #include "spdlog/async.h"

    int main() {
        auto console = spdlog::stdout_color_mt("console");
        spdlog::set_async_mode(1048576, spdlog::async_overflow_policy::block);
        spdlog::info("Hello, world!");
        return 0;
    }
    ```

